Problem Statement¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective:¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions:¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description:¶

  • Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.

def perc_on_bar(z):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''

    total = len(df[z]) # length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    ax = sns.countplot(df[z],palette='Paired')
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

K-means clustering

Figure out right number of cluster using elbow curve¶

In [149]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction=model.predict(subset_scaled_df)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(subset_scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) 
                           / subset_scaled_df.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[149]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

  • We can see a nice elbow forming around 3. So lets have 3 clusters

Finding right number of clusters using Silhouette score¶

In [150]:
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2,10))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((subset_scaled_df))
    #centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(subset_scaled_df, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {})".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list,sil_score)
plt.grid()

Hierarchical clustering

Calculating cophenet index for various Linkage and Distance measuring methods¶

In [164]:
# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on 
# dendrogram closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
distance_metrics = [ 'euclidean','chebyshev','mahalanobis','cityblock']
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
        print('Cophent correlation for distance metrics {} and linkage method {} is {}'.format(dm,lm,c))
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average','median','ward', 'weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]

for lm in linkage_methods:
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=lm)
    c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    print('Cophent correlation for distance metrics {} and linkage method {} is {}'.format('euclidean',lm,c))
    if high_cophenet_corr < c:
        high_cophenet_corr = c
        high_dm_lm[0] = dm
        high_dm_lm[1] = lm
print('*'*110)

Dendrogram of different linkage method¶

In [167]:
# List of all linkage methods to check
plt.rcParams["axes.grid"] = False
methods = ['single',
           'average', 
           'complete',
           'centroid',
           'ward',
           'weighted']

# Calculate the pairwise distance form the dataset to be used in the cophenetic correlation calculation
#pw_distance = pdist(credit_scaled)

# Create lists to save results of coph calculation
compare_cols = ['Linkage', 'Cophenetic Coefficient']
compare = []

# Create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# Enumerate through the list of all methods above
# Get linkage, plot dendrogram, calculate cophenetic coefficient
for i, method in enumerate(methods):
    
    Z = linkage(subset_scaled_df, metric='euclidean', method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i]);
    axs[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)')
    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(subset_scaled_df))
    axs[i].annotate(f'Cophenetic\nCoefficient\n{coph_corr:0.2f}', 
                    (0.80, 0.80),
                    xycoords='axes fraction')
    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Observations

  • Dendrogram with ward linkage method shows distinct and separate cluster

# lets replace 0,1,2 clusters with meaningful grades so that its easy to identify which record falls in which cluster
df['HC_Clusters']=df['HC_Clusters'].replace(2, 'A')#'A' for High Credit limit
df['HC_Clusters']=df['HC_Clusters'].replace(0, 'B')#'B' for Medium Credit limit

Insights about different clusters

  • Both the clusters have classified the same number of records in each segment
  • Segment A
    • has maximum credit limit 178000 and minimum credit limit 84000
    • has Average credit limit of approx 133069.76
    • customers have close to 9 credit cards on an average
    • customers make between 0 to 1 visits to bank
    • customers make around 11 visits online
    • customers make around 1 call
    • has only 43 customers
  • Segment B
    • Segment B has maximum credit limit 100000 and minimum credit limit 5000
    • Segment B has Average credit limit of approx 34071.42
    • customers have between 5 to 6 credit cards on an average
    • customers make between 3 to 4 visits to bank
    • customers make around 1 visits online
    • customers make around 2 calls
    • has maximum number of 378 customers
  • Segment C
    • Segment C has maximum credit limit 50000 and minimum credit limit 3000
    • Segment C has Average credit limit of approx 12239.81
    • customers have between 2 to 3 credit cards on an average
    • customers make around 1 visits to bank
    • customers make between 3 to 4 visits online
    • customers make around 7 calls
    • has 221 customers

Recommendations¶

For Marketting department

  • Segment A are highend customers. They need high credit limit.
  • Segment A customers already carry around 9 credit cards so they might not mind having 1 more.So its while selling them it should be kept in mind.
  • Segment B customers are the maximim in number and are middle class. So they should be targetted the most
  • Segment B customers have 5-6 cards already. so they might not be willing to keep more cards. So while selling cards to them we should be able to show benefit of keeping our card. Like low interest rate or interest free for 'X' number of days
  • Segment C has second highest number of customers so they should be also given lot of attention. They are from low income group
  • Segment C already have 2-3 cards and given their low income they might be very reluctant to keep another card. So we should give them some offers like cash back or discounts in restaurants,groceries etc

For Delivery department

  • Class A customers mainly prefer online banking because they dont have time to goto bank. So online user experience should be improved for such customers like maybe provide a chat service or chat bots
  • Class B customers who are mainly middle class have lot of time to goto bank and also they might be technically challenged to use online services. So to improve their experience we should provide fast services like having more staff, or automatic passbook entry machines or may I help you kiosk or maybe assign a dedicated mobile staff who can help them out in filling forms etc
  • Class C customers prefer to do banking on phone as they might not have conveyance to travel to their nearest branch frequently and they might be technically challenged to use online services.Possibility are they are old people with low income. TO improve their phone experience we can provide IVR service in their own mothertongue language. Also need to provide less options so that they dont get confused which button to press. Also to ensure low wait time we need to deploy more customer service representatives.
